      <hedline>
        <hl1>Batting the Breeze</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Charles Clarke letter on David Carkett's July 23 On Language question about origins of 'counterfactual' present tense in sports holds it might have followed advent of VCR and ESPN0</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>David Carkeet is puzzled by the origins of the ''counterfactual'' present tense used in sports (On Language, July 23). ''If the ball clears the fence, we win'' -- but it didn't, so we didn't.</p>
        <p>It seems obvious that such a construction is perfectly natural, even fitting, when superimposed over instant-replay video clips of the ball not clearing the fence. I would bet that the advent of the VCR and ESPN gave rise to this newly identified verb tense. (The earliest citation Carkeet gives, 1984, lends some support to this notion.)</p>
        <p>Charles Clarke  Oakland, Calif.</p>
      </block>
